Growing up I always thought we were running late because of my mom. She was always the last one in the car. “Oh mom just had to use the restroom.” “Guess who is the last one out of the house!”

It was always just a cheeky joke, I just thought.. maybe she was just moving slow. 

Here I am, many years later. A mom of three sweet boys, and often times the last one out of the house. 

While everyone is snug in the car, ready to go, I learned just why mom was always the last one out of the house.

My mom was the last one out of the house for the same reason I am….

Filling the water bottles because the second the car moves the littles need water.

Packing lunches, and endless snacks for the adventure to come.

Flushing the toilet for the little who forgot just five minutes ago. 

Turning off the lights in every room.

Packing extra clothes, diapers, wipes and jackets just incase. 

*a knock at the door*”MOM! Are you ready yet!! I want to go.”

Just another minute, I need to fill the water for the dogs, grab coffee for dad, put the breakfast away, grab the coupons for the grocery store, get the camera to capture memories…

“Mommy, let’s go!” 

Grab the keys.. lock the door.. wonder what you have forgotten. 

I always wondered why mom was the last one out of the house.. but then I became a mom and realized the whole time I thought she was thinking about herself…. She was actually thinking about everything else. 

She always put us first, and herself last. Thank you mom, I hope to be half the mother and wife you are.

I lied on my first postpartum screening.
Yup. I filled out the survey, and knew what it was acting. Maybe I was lying to myself? Maybe I was ashamed that I wasn’t all sunshine and smiles postpartum.

After all I just got home with a beautiful 5lb 12 ounce boy. He was perfect in every way. I had a spouse who was supportive, and I got to spend my days with endless snuggles…..

So why did I feel… like I had lost my identity? Like I wasn’t cut out for motherhood, why did I feel like I couldn’t do anything right? There were no silent nights, the crying on end was like nails on a chalkboard and I was anxious at every decision. So, when I went in to my six week visit and filled out the postpartum mental health form… I lied on it, or to myself. 

Thankfully I had a spouse who supported me, and encouraged me to be honest with myself. I also had the most amazing OBGYN and he supported me when I came back a few weeks later for help. 

Im not sure what I thought would happen. I didn’t face any judgement, I was met with support from professionals. Many mothers who I have talked to since have also struggled at some point with PPA/PPD. I thought I would be alone, but opening up brought me a world of support and community. 

It came back when I gave birth to my second, and was in full swing during my pregnancy with my third. Im now 2 years postpartum and still taking meds for my mental health. I suffer from OCD and anxiety and postpartum just made those more challenging. Having a provider who supports me, a spouse who checks in on me and a family who has normalized talking about mental health has been a game changer in my journey. 

So mama, if your newly postpartum - and your struggling… you are not alone. If you need to talk.. I am here 🤍

Yesterday we drove 1.5 hours to @dollywood and almost turned around before we made it to the gate. It was the busiest it’s been out of all the times we have gone. I tried to pay for preferred parking but it was already sold out. I drive flustered for my husband to drop us off because there was no chance of our son riding the tram. The lady who was just doing her job tried to force us in a different direction. Flustered and almost in tears I yelled, “we are just trying to go to the drop off, my son won’t ride the tram”. People don’t get it, he can love rollercoasters all day long and still hate waiting in line for a tram and sitting close to people he doesn’t know and while not having his safe space (his @wonderfoldwagon). 

A kind employee saw the distress in my eyes while I paused and asked if there was any chance they would allow us to park near the handicap parking. She ushered us through, and once again I remembered why I’ll choose @dollywood over anywhere else. 

We packed our wagon with all our essentials: our @spioworks, noise canceling headphones, special food and our tablet. Once we made it inside we went to the disability access center. I asked for a card for the calming room because we were already off to a rough start… I bring our passes from the prior visit because measuring doesn’t always go smoothly. This pass allows my son and our family to wait outside of the line. Yes, for most rides we still have to wait the wait time like everyone else, but he’s able to do so while in his wagon, playing on a playground or riding a different ride. You see, he loves rollercoasters, he loves driving the cars on the raceway… but if he had to wait next to you in line we would probably have to leave in tears before our turn 9/10 times.

“Why do they get to walk right on.” 
“I wonder if she’s faking it to get a fast pass.”
“They should have to wait in line like the rest of us.”

These comments are so common. We go monthly because Dollywood is one of the few places my kids feel safe, and respected to be who they are. So before you judge a family on an invisible disability please remember most of us would rather be able to wait in the line with our littles.

Please. Wish me luck.

Adderall almost ruined my marriage. 

Of course, every medication affects each person differently. For me, this was not the right choice. I wanted to share my experience so that people would know that they are not alone.

I felt productive, like I was finally able to keep up with the world around me. But the questions haunted me… Why wouldn’t my husband do more at home? Why didn’t my kids just listen to me? Why was everything just so difficult? Why did every little thing irritate me?

When my husband approached me about how I had changed since I started back on Medication I ignored him. Time and time again he gently brought it up… until I listened. 

I agreed to a trial without my medication to see how I felt, and nobody was more surprised than myself. I felt relief, the irritation lifted, I wasn’t on edge all the time. I enjoyed being around my children and my spouse and no longer resented everything they did. 

Sometimes society’s solution to the problem isn’t the solution to your problems.

I’m still trying to figure out a balance for myself, but I wanted to take the time to say it’s okay to step back and try something new.

Sourdough discard dinner rolls:

1/2 cup warm water
2 tsp active yeast
2 eggs
2 TBS olive oil
1 cup sourdough discard 
1 tsp salt
3 1/2 cups @kingarthurbaking flour
2 tsp sugar 
( plus one egg for egg wash) 

-add warm water to stand mixer, sprinkle the yeast and sugar on the top. Let the yeast activate for 3-4 min.
-add 2 eggs, salt, olive oil and sourdough starter. Mis until just combined.
- add the bread hook attachment and slowly add flour 1 cup at a time. Once all flour is combined turn the speed up on your mixer. 
- using the mixer knead the dough for 3-5 minutes until smooth and gently pulling from the bowl.
-place dough in a greased bowl in a warm area for about one hour (or until doubled!)
-once the bread has coupled create 15 balls and place in a greased 9” x 13” pan. Allow the rolls to rest an additional 30 minutes or until doubled in size.
-combine the last egg with a splash of water and brush the tops of the rolls.
-preheat oven to 375 and cook rolls for 15-20 minutes. 

Serve warm with sweet or savory spread.

I used to be afraid to have a sourdough starter. My ADHD brain would forget to feed it, and I always thought it would die…  but I love the routine of feeding it every day, and I love the excitement that comes when I make my own bread. 

Feeding a sourdough starter is easy I use the king Arthur Recipe and on weeks that I don’t plan on baking I put my sourdough starter in the fridge and only have to feed it once a week. I also took the time to dehydrate some of my starter so that if I get to a period where I’m not taking care of it. I can always re-hydrate and start over.

Feeding your starter: 

113 grams sourdough starter
113 grams @kingarthurbaking flour
113 grams room temp water

Mix in a clean jar and allow to double in size. You may have to adjust water and flour amounts depending on time of year and humidity in your house.

I’m one of those people who never cries in a doctors appointment, but as soon as I get in the car the floodgates open.

My little was 16 months old, and recovering from his second surgery when we found out he had a CHD. I remember it clear as day. We went in for a complication from his surgery, and our primary physician wasn’t there. We had a sweet older doctor who informed me that my son had a heart murmur, but it was probably nothing to worry about… many children have heart murmurs. I knew otherwise… it’s that feeling, you know? 

My husband and I took our son to the cardiologist. We checked in, he was in the 90th percentile for height and had the sweetest smile. They did an EKG, and an Echo. My dear boy was so brave. We sat in the room as muffled voices talked in the hall. I looked at my husband, we knew - something wasn’t quiet right. He drew a diagram, and used medical terminology I didn’t understand. I sat there frozen - unsure of what to ask. 

You see, our son had an ASD. A large hole in his heart that required closure via surgery. Later we learned that there is more - a mutation on a gene that will require ongoing cardiology research, monitoring and possible procedures for his entire life. 

I’ve gotten better about not crying after appointments. I don’t want to say you become numb to the constant surprises, the endless consults with specialists, or the hoops you have to jump through for every minor thing… but the truth is.. with each appointment your skin grows a little thicker. You channel that fear of the unknown into advocating for your child… for finding options.. you channel that fear into love. 

In honor of #nationalheartmonth I challenge you to learn a little about CHDs. I’ll be sharing facts, and our story over the next week. I hope you will join me.

I scheduled two appointments for two different children, with two different specialists…. At the same time on the same day. 

I’ve been waiting six months for these appointments and somehow until now I didn’t realize I would need to be in two places at once. Both appointments are incredibly important, and have been difficult to schedule and get into - so which kid do I prioritize? Which kid gets to keep their appointment while the other needs to be scheduled out probably another 4-6 months.

There is nothing I can do, so I laughed… then cried. 

This is the system we live in as medical families. Endless appointments, therapies, fighting insurance, and scheduling conflicts. So we triage, we go with what is the most immediate need. We add ourselves to cancelation lists, and hope they hire more staff. We wait months for appointments to be told we need a different specialist. Then we wake up and do it all again.
I want to live a life like moose 🫶
Living that boy mom life, snuggles and all.

Use this cake recipe & layer with homemade whipped cream and fresh strawberries. I also love to use @rich_products for my topping. 

2 1/2 cups flour
1 teaspoon baking powder
1/2 teaspoon table salt
1/4 teaspoon baking soda
1 cup softened butter
4 large eggs
1 cup buttermilk
1 tablespoon almond or vanilla extract
2 cups sugar

Preheat oven to 350°
Mix on medium high speed all wet ingredients
Slowly mix in dry ingredients. 
Separate mix into 3 greased round cake pans
Bake for 30 min.
Let cool & layer with whipped topping and strawberries.

June is National Dairy Month and I’ve partnered with @MilkMeansMore to share one of my favorite summer recipes, strawberry milk tea. #AD Enjoy every day this summer by indulging in fun dairy creations with your loved ones to make delicious memories!

Here is what you need:

1 cup chopped strawberries 

1TBS sugar

1TBS water

2 green or black tea bags

1/2 cup whole milk

1/4 cup prepared boba

1 scoop vanilla ice cream

Handful of ice cubes

Directions:

Create a strawberry simple syrup by cooking fresh strawberries, sugar, and water together over low heat. When that has simmered purée, strain and allow to cool.

In a drinking glass add your prepared boba, a few fresh-cut strawberries, cooled green or black tea, and the strawberry simple syrup. Top with whole milk & stir until combined.

Add a scoop of vanilla ice cream and enjoy!

Growing up, I learned how to make pierogies. It’s some thing that we had at every family gathering. Polish food is my comfort zone. Food that warms my heart and soul. 

Here is my simple pierogi recipe: 

For the dough mix together: 1 egg, 1/2 cup sour cream, 1/4 cup butter, pinch of salt & two cups flour.

For the filling:
Sauerkraut & sour cream (remove excess liquid from the sauerkraut)
Meat (shredded pot roast)
Farmers cheese (homemade or store bought)
Mashed potatoes & cheese

You ever feel like you’re not being listened to by the system? Like your just another number in the queue of people they need to get through. A faceless task to be checked off? An empty box on a medical chart?

Don’t get me wrong. We have had our fair share of AMAZING providers. & I recommend them over and over to moms in the medical and special needs community… because when you find a good one you make sure everyone knows they actually care. 

& we have even had good experiences with @missionhealthnc children’s before. But this week was far less then a good experience. I don’t know where the ball dropped first. But I’m here to tell you a patient and physician relationship is developed when the provider affirmatively acts in a patients case. That might be via consult, exam or by diagnosing or agreeing to treat said patient. So to refuse to let a patient leave a message for an on call provider who consulted on their case less than 24 hours before about an urgent concern (essentially forcing them back to the ER) because they are not an “established” patient doesn’t sit right ethically. 

Friends, when it comes to your littles fight for them, don’t let the system limit or delay your right to care. & if you ever question the care you’re getting. Ask for a patient advocate.

One goal I’ve had for the new year is to cook more homemade meals. I’ll be honest... with the kids home from holiday break & the. Home yesterday and today due to weather I’ve... Slacked in that department.

One meal that will be on a weekly rotation is this easy roast chicken. I cooked mine in our cast iron Dutch oven.

Start by making sure your cast iron Dutch oven is seasoned.
Then add 1 yellow onion, 2 full carrots and 2 celery stalks to the bottom. Drizzle with olive oil.

Place the whole chicken on top of the vegetables and drizzle with olive oil, cracked black pepper, Himalayan sea salt, fresh thyme, fresh rosemary and sprinkle a few red chili flakes on top. Add 1 cup broth to the bottom of the pan.

For a 3-4 lb chicken preheat the oven to 375°. Cover with the lid and add your dish to the oven. Cook covered for 45 minutes to an hour. Remove the lid and cook an additional
30-45 minutes depending on the size. Remove the chicken from the oven and be sure it has reached proper internal temperatures. Let it rest for 10 min then serve.

When you have finished with the chicken use the bones, the carrots, celery, onion and broth from the pan and add it to the instant pot to make broth. Can your broth or store in the fridge to be used within a week. Homemade bone broth is wonderful this time of year! I honestly love to just sip it when I feel a cold or sickness coming on!
